'''John Gregory McKee''' is a [[New Zealand]] [[rugby union]] coach, who is currently the head coach of the [[Fiji national rugby union team|Fiji]] national team.

==Career==
McKee has been coaching since the late 1990s in [[Australia]], but left in 2000 to coach French side [[ASM Clermont Auvergne|AS Montferrand]] ''(now known as ASM Clermont Auvergne)''. In doing so, he led the team to the final of the [[2000–01 French Rugby Union Championship]], but lost 34-22 to [[Stade Toulousain|Toulouse]]. In 2002 he became assistant coach of [[Connacht Rugby|Connacht]] under [[Michael Bradley (rugby union)|Michael Bradley]]. McKee and Bradley led Connacht to the Quarter Finals of the [[2002–03 Celtic League]] and the [[2002–03 European Challenge Cup]], before leading the side to two consecutive Semi Finals in the [[European Challenge Cup]]; [[2003–04 European Challenge Cup|2003–04]] and [[2004–05 European Challenge Cup|2004–05]]. He left Ireland in 2005 to take over [[Cornish Pirates]] in the [[2005–06 National Division One]], finishing third behind [[Bedford Blues]] and [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]].

In 2007 he returned to Australia as the head coach of [[Central Coast Rays]] in the inaugural and sole [[Australian Rugby Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsrugby.com/news/6117.php#.U2PS4_YU_IU |title=Coach John McKee has returned Down Under after a successful six-year stint in Europe to link up with the New South Wales Central Coast franchise in the inaugural Australian Rugby Championship.|accessdate=2 May 2014|publisher=The British & Irish Lions}}</ref> The Rays finished second behind the [[Greater Sydney Rams#ARC: Western Sydney Rams|Western Sydney Rams]] in the normal season, but finished on top at the final against [[Melbourne Rebels (ARC)|Melbourne Rebels]], winning 20-12. When the ARC became defunct, McKee travelled with the [[Pacific Islanders rugby union team]] on their [[2008 Pacific Islanders rugby union tour of Europe|2008 European tour]] as a Specialist Coach. This tour included a record first-ever victory for the side, winning 25–17 against [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/scrum/rugby/story/86858.html|title=Pacific Islands record first-ever victory|accessdate=2 May 2014|publisher=ESBN.co.uk|date=22 November 2008}}</ref> He furthered his international experience when he was named the Technical Advisor for [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]] in the year leading up to and during the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tongarugbyunion.net/main/rwc-team-and-management/|title=RWC Team and Management|accessdate=2 May 2014|publisher=Tonga Rugby Union}}</ref>

After working with Tonga, he took up the role of Programs Coach at the Australian Rugby Union, where he was involved in developing and delivering rugby programs for 18- to 22-year-old players in the ARU National Academy Program. This also meant he was the assistant coach for the [[Australia national under-20 rugby union team|Australian Under-20]]'s side in the [[2013 IRB Junior World Championship]] in [[France]], Australia finished seventh.

He is an [[Australian Rugby Union]] Level 3 coach and has a [[New Zealand Rugby Union|NZRU]]-[[Massey University]] Diploma of Management. He has an Australian Strength and Conditioning Association Level 1 Coaching certification, and has a Fitness Instructor Certification from [[Monash University]].

===Fiji===
In November 2013, McKee was appointed as the [[Fiji Rugby Union]] (FRU) High Performance Unit general manager with the goal to get Fiji into the top eight of the [[IRB World Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=251859|title=McKee to head Fiji rugby HPU|accessdate=2 May 2014|date=19 November 2013|work=The Fiji Times}}</ref> However, when the then head coach [[Inoke Male]] was sacked by the FRU due to financial issues, McKee expressed his desire in succeeding Male in February 2014, hoping that as head coach he could do more to help Fiji into the top eight of the World Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/other/rugby/story/212261.html|title=Cash-strapped Fiji sack coach Male|accessdate=2 May 2014|publisher=ESBN.co.uk|date=27 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijione.tv/mckee-interested-in-flying-fijians-coaching-job/|title=McKee interested in Flying Fijian’s Coaching job|accessdate=2 May 2014|date=11 February 2014|publisher=FijiOne}}</ref> On 2 May 2014, McKee was officially announced as the Flying Fijians head coach, cutting short his three-year contract as High Performance Unit general manager, and would lead the team into the final [[2015 Rugby World Cup – Oceania qualification#Round 2: Oceania Final|2015 Rugby World Cup qualification match]] against the [[Cook Islands national rugby union team|Cook Islands]] in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fijirugby.com/pages.cfm/fru-news/?section=2013&newsid=fru-appoints-new-flying-fijians-head-coach|title=FRU Appoints New Flying Fijians Head Coach|accessdate=2 May 2014|date=2 May 2014|publisher=FijiRugby.com|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140502171812/http://www.fijirugby.com/pages.cfm/fru-news/?section=2013&newsid=fru-appoints-new-flying-fijians-head-coach|archivedate=2 May 2014|df=}}</ref>

In McKee's first match in charge, he led Fiji to a 25–14 win over [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]], Fiji's first win over a Tier 1 team since their 38–34 win over [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] in the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]]. In addition to this, he also led Fiji to first in the Pacific Islands conference of the [[2014 IRB Pacific Nations Cup]]. This included a 45–17 win over [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]] and a 13–18 loss to [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]]. He coached the team to a 108–6 win over the Cook Islands in the [[2015 Rugby World Cup – Oceania qualification|2015 Rugby World Cup Oceania qualification]] process, thus qualifying for England 2015, joining [[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A|Pool A]]. During Fiji's [[2014 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2014 European tour]], McKee led the team to just one victory, coming against the United States winning 20–14. They had lost before this match, losing to [[France national rugby union team|France]] 40–15 and narrowly to [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] 17–13.

In 2015, McKee led the team to victory in the [[2015 World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup]], where Fiji beat Tonga 30–22 and Japan 27–22, while also drawing with Samoa 30–30. The Fiji-Samoa game was repeated again in the final, which saw Fiji out score Samoa 5 tries to 3, winning 39–29. McKee later led Fiji into the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]], where despite only picking up one win, 47–15 win over [[Uruguay national rugby union team|Uruguay]], Fiji was largely competitive in all 4 matches, holding Wales to a 23–13 win and [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] to 28–13. McKee was linked with the Japan post, but McKee dismissed the rumours announcing that he would seek renewal of is contract through to the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>[http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/news/107525 I'm staying with Fiji, says coach John McKee as he dismisses rumours about Japan]</ref>

In 2016, McKee lead Fiji to their third consecutive Pacific Nations Cup title, having beaten Tonga 23–18, after being down 15–0 at half time, and defeating Samoa 26–16. However, on 24 June, Fiji lost against [[Georgia national rugby union team|Georgia]] for the first time, losing 14–3. During their [[2016 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2016 end-of-year tour]], Fiji gained a single win across 3 matches, coming in the final week against Japan 38–25. The other games saw Fiji get defeated by England, 58–15 and the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] 40–7.

In [[2017 mid-year rugby union internationals|June 2017]], Fiji was the only Tier 2 nation to play three Tier 1 internationals; Australia, Italy and [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]. McKee led Fiji to two victories, their homes tests against Italy, 22–19, and Scotland, 27–22. It was the first ever time that Fiji had beaten more than one Tier 1 team in a single calendar year, while also beating Scotland for the first time since 1998. The Australian test saw Fiji lose to Australia in [[Melbourne]] 37–14. On 8 July 2017, McKee helped Fiji qualify for the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] after beating Tonga 14–10 during the [[2017 World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup]]. A week later with a 38–16 victory over Samoa saw Fiji retain their PNC title for a third consecutive year. Fiji continued their good form into their [[2017 end-of-year rugby union internationals|End-of-year European tour]], narrowly losing Tier 1 sides Italy, 19–10, and [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]] 23–20. Fiji's only victory came in their final test on tour, defeating Canada 57–17, which was a record winning margin for Fiji over the Canadians.

In June 2018, McKee led Fiji to their fourth consecutive Pacific Nations title, after beating Samoa 24–22 in the opening round and newcomers Georgia 37–15 in the second round. However, On 23 June, Fiji lost to Tonga for the first time since 2011 27–19, in a one-off test match outside the PNC.

====Honours====
*'''[[World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup]]'''
**Winners: 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018
**Runners-up: 2014 (joint with USA)

